treasures:
Th' greed that has driven us t' these islands now forces us t' stay here. Day after day we search fer th' booty that brought us t' these lands t' begin with. Our group o' men have discovered several different types o' booty, some even from slayin' th' ravenous indigenous creatures that seem t' roam these islands and caves. But we cannot seem t' leave, we need more. Th' island and its spirits demand it.

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' next pages seem t' be ripped out and missin'./}}

We have failed. Many have perished. We be missin' th' final piece. I do not think we can make it much further. We seem t' have angered nature itself.

oldGods:
Th' same three strange symbols seem t' appear again and again on artifacts, cave walls, and ruined altars. Cross-referencin' old texts and journals we have found mentions o' deities, spirits, and even Gods. Most likely worshiped by th' heathens that used t' inhabit these lands. They seem connected t' these islands somehow.

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' next page has crude drawings o' th' three symbols./}}

{$DEITY:EVIL} {$DEITY:CHAOS} {$DEITY:GOOD}

sandCasting:
{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' entire book seems t' be stained with various chemicals and powders./}}

Throughout me metallurgic experiments, I have found th' best way t' forge metal-based tools and weapons was t' use a metal castin' technique. Usin' th' resources aroun' me, I have found that sand castin' was th' best method.

Th' primary ingredient fer creatin' a sand cast be green sand, a mixture o' clay flakes, and refined sand. This allows fer th' malleability o' creatin' th' shape o' tool and weapon heads.

Next, we place th' green sand in a flask, crafted with wood, holystone, granite, or raw clay, finishin' th' build o' th' sand cast flask. We then set th' shape, place down some talc powder so th' finished produce can be lifted easier, and pour th' molten smelted mixture into th' cast t' let it set and harden.

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' book be adorned with crude drawings o' each process./}}

I have also found I can use limestone powder as th' flux t' refine ores and remove impurities in th' smeltin' process. Some carbon powder can also be used t' get a proper hardness t' th' finished metal. Not all metals need a flux or carbon treatment however.

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' bottom o' th' paged be signed with:/}}

- James Townsend, th' Smithy

