trapped:
One would assume I would be able t' make it back home, or at least a bit further from these strange islands. But try as I might with this ramshackle raft, I am unable t' get very far. I somehow always lose me bearin'. Th' horizon becomes unclear and me surroundings blurry. Next thin' ye know, I come across another set o' islands that be completely unfamiliar t' me.

I am unable t' explain this. Me charts and maps be correct! I am sure o' it. Somebody, or {/somethin'/} be hinderin' me progress t' go back home.

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' rest o' th' book be water damaged and most o' th' writin' be illegible./}}

onWaterAndHydration:
{/There's water in th' ground./}
{/There's water in th' cave./}
{/If I go thirsty./}
{/I'll soon come across me grave./}
{/There's water in th' well./}
{/There's water in th' sea./}
{/Shall I go thirsty?/}
{/We shall very well see./}

Water be found in many places, but not all forms be safe t' drink. Take fer example yer ne'er-endin' horizontal surroundin'; th' sea. It would be so easy if ye were able t' drink th' salty brine, but even in a dire situation, it can often be deadly. It will cause distress t' yer insides and make ye even thirstier. What type o' gods found delight in such a thin'?

Thar be a workaround, however. Constructin' a still will allow ye t' desalinate th' water by distillin' it. Boilin' th' water fer lon' periods o' time will cause th' filtered steam t' collect in a separate vessel, resultin' in nearly pure water. Show those gods what fer!

Or perhaps ye can come across water on land. Water be commonly found in swampy areas and near rocks, especially in high elevation areas whar snow may form. Snow be water after all! Water be also commonly abundant in subterranean caves. These forms o' water may be safe t' drink, but it's always a good idea t' boil fresh water. This will require a fire source. Diggin' can also sometimes provide hidden underground water, especially near other bodies o' pre-existin' water like ponds and lakes.

Fer th' more industrious type, ye may fancy a well. Wells will be able t' accumulate rain and ground water, although not all terrain be suitable fer their construction. Findin' a ground water source may be taxin' on resources, especially when ye be not able t' map some godforsaken subterranean passages below.

So ye see, water be everywhere, ye just need t' know whar t' look.

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' book ends with a signed name:/}}

- Henry Cliffe

travelingBySea:
{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' first page contains a centered preface./}}

{_Consider this a first draft._}

I have made me peace with th' fact that I will remain lost t' civilization, but at least I will not be lost at sea. Me first attempts with a raft ended in failure, wanderin' in circles, and almost losin' a limb t' a shark. I then constructed a bull boat, which helped me cross more distant stretches o' water.

Upon me island wanderin', I came across a sextant in an abandoned house. In another set o' islands, I then stumbled upon a spyglass. Both items have come in great help when traversin' th' sea. I use me sextant t' plot me course and stay on target and use me spyglass t' spot new land on th' horizon.

Before I found them, I was strugglin' t' come across new land, and exhaustin' me food and water.

darknessCalls:
{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Th' entire book seems stained with black soot. Some pages be entirely blackened with various stains./}}

As I explored th' caves and below-ground subterranean passages, I often heard voices through th' rocks. I played it up as nerves at first. After several days I decided t' give in t' this madness and work me way through th' rock and rubble, minin' away into th' earth with much fury.

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Two pages appear t' be ripped out here./}}

Their hands were like fiery hot bludgeonin' needles, proddin' and scrapin' me skin leavin' me with frostbite. Th' amalgamation o' every malady and pain I have ever felt in me many years here. A strange sensation t' be sure.

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:{/Yet another page was ripped out in this section./}}

And what be this that they produce? Somethin' so dark and ephemeral I could barely see it floatin' above th' void.

Dark on dark on dark.

